        depth: 1,
        title: "The Mind That Cuts Corners",
        body: `<p>A friend tells you about a plane crash on the morning news. That afternoon, at the airport, your hand tightens on the armrest. The statistics have not changed. Flying is, this afternoon as yesterday, one of the safest things a human being can do. But something in you has tilted, almost imperceptibly, away from the numbers and toward the picture.</p><p>This is not stupidity. It is the ordinary architecture of human thought. The mind that lets you read this sentence, recognize your mother's voice in a noisy room, and decide in half a second whether a stranger is a threat — that mind is built on shortcuts. Most of them are brilliant. Some of them, in the wrong context, are very nearly catastrophic.</p><p>The study of these shortcuts is one of the youngest and most disquieting branches of psychology. It asks, with a kind of patient cruelty: what would we believe, decide, and remember if we could see ourselves clearly? The answer, again and again, is: not quite what we believe, decide, and remember now.</p>`,
