        depth: 5,
        title: "Prospect Theory and the Shape of the Value Function",
        body: `<p>Prospect theory is the most mathematically developed account of decision under risk in modern psychology, and the keystone of behavioral economics. It is worth seeing it in slightly formal dress.</p><p>Classical expected-utility theory, descending from Bernoulli and von Neumann-Morgenstern, holds that a rational agent evaluates a risky prospect by computing the probability-weighted sum of the utilities of its outcomes:</p><pre><code>EU(prospect) = sum over i of  p_i * u(x_i)

where u(x) is a utility function defined over
total wealth, typically concave (diminishing
marginal utility).</code></pre><p>Kahneman and Tversky's 1979 <em>Econometrica</em> paper, <em>Prospect Theory: An Analysis of Decision under Risk</em>, showed in a series of elegant experiments that real people do not do this. Three robust departures stand out.</p><p>First, the carriers of value are not states of total wealth but <em>changes</em> from a reference point — typically the status quo. Second, the value function is concave for gains, convex for losses, and steeper for losses than for gains. Third, probabilities are not used directly but transformed by a <em>weighting function</em> that overweights small probabilities and underweights moderate-to-large ones.</p><pre><code>V(prospect) = sum over i of  w(p_i) * v(x_i)

where v(x) is the value function:

           v(x)
             |              .--------
             |          .---'
             |       .-'
             |     .'                  (gains: concave)
             |   .'
   ----------+----------------- x
            .|
          .' |
        .'   |
      .'     |                         (losses: convex, steeper)
    .'       |
  -'         |

and w(p) is the probability weighting function,
S-shaped, overweighting small p and underweighting
moderate-to-large p:

  w(0.01) ~ 0.05    (a 1% chance feels like ~5%)
  w(0.40) ~ 0.35    (a 40% chance feels like ~35%)
  w(0.99) ~ 0.95    (a 99% chance feels like ~95%)</code></pre><p>The kink at the reference point — the fact that the curve bends sharply at zero — is the formal expression of loss aversion. Empirically the loss multiplier <em>lambda</em> is typically estimated at around 2.0 to 2.5: losses hurt roughly twice as much as equivalent gains feel good. This single asymmetry explains an astonishing range of phenomena: the equity premium puzzle in finance, the endowment effect (people demand more to sell an object than they would pay to buy it), the status quo bias, and the disposition effect (investors hold losing stocks too long and sell winners too quickly).</p><p>The probability weighting function explains the simultaneous popularity of lotteries (tiny p of huge gain, overweighted) and insurance (tiny p of huge loss, overweighted) in the same household — a combination that violates expected-utility theory but follows naturally from prospect theory.</p><p>Cumulative Prospect Theory (Tversky and Kahneman, 1992) generalized the framework to handle prospects with many outcomes and rank-dependent weighting. The model is not perfect — recent work by Glöckner, Pachur, and others has identified systematic deviations — but it remains the most empirically successful descriptive theory of risky choice ever proposed, and the conceptual core of what won Kahneman the Nobel.</p>`
